text: Eesh. I wanna say this looks good but...Jackie Chan doesn't look like he wants to be in this movie. Its good to see him in a new action movie, or just in a movie at all. He can still pull off stunts, which is impressive considering his age, but he doesn't look like he's giving a lot of energy unlike all his other movies, whether they were good or bad. Also, I don't mind the old Taken style, straight-forward revenge plot, only if they use it in a good, fresh way. Also, the cinematography kinda looks bland and dull and the CGI isn't at all convincing. But that's just my opinion. I know it seems like I'm trashing this movie without having seen it and going into maybe too much detail into just a 2 minute long trailer for what is supposed to be a straight forward, fun action thriller, but I wanna stay optimistic because Jackie Chan is a legend. I just wanna see him in a good movie after a long time.

text: I've commented this before on one of the Atomic Blonde trailers but I'll say it again. With two John Wick movies, Atomic Blonde, American Assassin and now The Foreigner, it seems as though Hollywood is giving us a lot of sleek looking, silent assassin movies starring big actors. Either they're starting a whole new unofficial genre like superhero/comic book movies, or all the studios behind each respective movie mentioned above are starting an Assassin Cinematic Universe. Now I know many of us are sick to death of connected universes but hear me out. What if they keep it unconfirmed? And in each movie, instead of obvious references to the other movies to keep them tied together, they drop subtle hints? Such as the gold coins that appear in the John Wick movies appearing in the other movies, or extras in the background talking about a man who killed three men in a bar with a pencil, the audio quietened down. Then, as people start to notice as the movies progress and start to post theories on the internet, as they do, start introducing bigger and more frequent references, like a file, which has John Wick or Charlize Theron's character in Atomic Blonde's name in small font size in the corner of a file. This is what connected universe's should be like. Instead of blatantly telling us what's coming next, they should keep us guessing. This would even fit with the tone of these movies and characters: dark, mysterious, subtle. The Pixar movies may all be connected. So might these suspiciously large amounts of assassin movies be. Who knows?
